This should apply to all the other three; but the absurdity of supposing that Tiberius contrived the fall of Piso makes Nipp. contend that the re- mark about him is parenthetical, and that only two out of the three originally men- tioned are referred to. In any case Tacitus oversteps his own facts, for Tiberius is admitted to have been prob· ably not eognisant of the charge against Arruntius (6. 47, 4); so that ‘ omnes' and ‘mox‘ are justified only by the fate of Gallus some sixteen years later, on which see note on 6. 23, 1.
